an, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Eatington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Edington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edington","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Edington in Northumberland, Somerset, and Wiltshire, or from Eddington, Berkshire. Edington in Northumberland arises from Old English <i>Idingtūn</i>, from the Old English personal name <i>Ida</i>, + <i>ing</i>, denoting association, + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’ (compare   Ida  ). In Somerset, the name comes either from the Old English male name <i>Ēadwine</i> or from the feminine <i>Ēadwynn</i> + <i>ing</i> + <i>tūn</i>. Edington (Wiltshire) is from either the Old English personal name <i>Ētha</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’, or from Old English <i>ēthe</i> ‘uncultivated’ + <i>dūn</i>."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon de E